Cancel Culture¶

Team Members: Allison DeSantis (ajd29), Klara Van Wamelen (klaravw), Sebastian Gonzalez Castro (srg4rv)

Cancel culture is the phenomenon of collectively shaming an individual (usually a celebrity or public figure) online in response to a controversial thing they said or did. Our goal is to analyze cancel culture in online communities.¶

Allison: collected Twitter data, did VADER sentiment analysis on cancel culture tweets and tweets from the canceled celebrities, attempted usinf LIWC to find anger and negative emotion words but did not include in final notebook.¶

Klara: collected YouTube data, did VADER sentiment analysis on YouTube comments, analyzed likes and views on YouTube videos¶

Sebastian: collected Instagram data, did VADER sentiment analysis on Instagram comments¶

We decided to analyze the cancel culture incidents involving James Charles and Cardi B. In phase 1, we were also going to analyze actor Jussie Smollett but decided not to because we weren't able to collect as much data for him. Smollett disabled his instagram comments so we could not collect comments on his Instagram posts. There were significantly less tweets and YouTube comments for Smollett as well. The function to collect the cancel culture tweets changed from phase 1 to phase 2 to include a search for tweets with the phrase IsOverParty to find #_celebrity_IsOverParty tweets and we got rid of the separate function to collect IsOverParty tweets. In phase 1, we collected tweets from 1-1-2019 until now. In phase 2, the twitter functions changed to take a list of tuples as a parameter. Each tuple in the list has a start date and an end date. The functions go through a loop and search for tweets from the start date until the end date for each tuple in the list. The first date range is 1-1-2019 to 5-1-2019 which is before the celebrities were canceled. The second date range is 6-1-2019 to 12-31-2019 which was after the celebrities were canceled. The last date range, 1-1-2020 to 4-27-2020, is sometime after the controversy and 'canceling' was the most intense. Because we are only analyzing two cancel culture incidents instead of three, we increased the max count of tweets to collect for each date range for each celebrity from 200 to 500. Before the data is cleaned, each function will collect 1500 tweets for each celebrity, so a total of 3000 tweets. For the YouTube part, we fixed up the cleaning of the data in phase 2 which allowed us to collect more data than in phase 1. For the Instagram part, we changed the functions to collect posts from a specific time period in phase 2 rather than the most recent posts and comments. We tried to use the LIWC dictionary to find angry and negative emotion words in the tweets but ran out of time. We tried to include older comments from Instagram posts but the API was taking too long to access those.

Our first research question and follow-up question are: Is cancel culture a negative phenomenon? Are there any positive aspects? We analyze this through sentiment analysis of cancel culture tweets and tweets from 'canceled' celebrities.¶

Part 1: Twitter¶

In order to analyze cancel culture tweets about a celebrity, we need to collect tweets that include cancel culture language. We collected data from two incidents of cancel culture in 2019. We chose to analyze James Charles (YouTube beauty guru) and Cardi B (rapper and songwriter), because these celebrities were both canceled in 2019 due to a controversial action.

Importing necessary libraries, like GetOldTweets3 to collect tweets from 2019.

The function get_cancel_tweets(names, count) takes in a list of celebrity names, a max tweet count, and a list of tuples containing start and end dates. It finds tweets that contain the celebrity's name and the word cancel or tweets that contain the celebrity's name followed by IsOverParty for each celebrity in the names list. The function loops through all tuples in the list of date ranges to find 500 tweets for each date range for each celebrity. This function allows us to find cancel culture tweets that include phrases like: 'James Charles is canceled', 'Cancel James Charles', 'James Charles is #canceled'. The list of date range tuples allows us to collect tweets from before the controversy involving James Charles surfaced in early-2019, during the time the controversy surfaced and he was being canceled in mid-2019, and most recently in 2020.

In [158]:
def get_cancel_tweets(names, count, time):
    
    post_id = []
    post_text = []
    author = []
    date = []
    retweet = []
    favorites = []
    canceled_celeb = []
    
    for date_range in time:
        for name in names:
            search = str('cancel ' + name)
            search2 = str(name + 'IsOverParty')
        
            tweetCriteria = got.manager.TweetCriteria().setQuerySearch(search). \
            setSince(date_range[0]).setUntil(date_range[1]).setMaxTweets(count)
        
            tweetCriteria2 = got.manager.TweetCriteria().setQuerySearch(search2). \
            setSince(date_range[0]).setUntil(date_range[1]).setMaxTweets(count)
        
            tweets = got.manager.TweetManager.getTweets(tweetCriteria)
            tweets2 = got.manager.TweetManager.getTweets(tweetCriteria2)
    
            for tweet in tweets: 
                post_id.append(tweet.id)
                post_text.append(tweet.text)
                author.append(tweet.username)
                date.append(tweet.date)
                retweet.append(tweet.retweets)
                favorites.append(tweet.favorites)
                canceled_celeb.append(name)
        
            for tweet in tweets2: 
                post_id.append(tweet.id)
                post_text.append(tweet.text)
                author.append(tweet.username)
                date.append(tweet.date)
                retweet.append(tweet.retweets)
                favorites.append(tweet.favorites)
                canceled_celeb.append(name)
    
    data = {'post_id':post_id, 'post_text':post_text, 'author':author, 'date':date, 
            'retweets':retweet, 'favorites':favorites, 'canceled_celeb':canceled_celeb}
    
    # data frames to hold tweets
    cancel_tweets = pd.DataFrame(data=data)
        
    return cancel_tweets

Some tweets that contain the word 'cancel' and the celebrites' names cannot actually be considered cancel culture tweets. The celebrities do concerts and tours. We don't care about tweets from fans on social media that pertain to a canceled concert or tour. We drop any tweets from the dataframe that contain the words concert, tour, show, live, or performance. We also drop tweets with duplicate post text from the dataframe and leave the first tweet with the post text. We save the cancel_tweets_clean dataframe to a csv.

# drop tweets with duplicate post text, keep the first one
duplicate_posts = cancel_tweets[cancel_tweets.duplicated(subset='post_text', keep='first')]

no_dups = cancel_tweets.drop(duplicate_posts.index)

# find tweets about concerts, tours, and shows
invalid_cancel_tweets = no_dups[no_dups.post_text.str.contains('concert|show|tour|performance|live')]

# drop tweets from df, likely not cancel culture tweets
cancel_tweets_clean = no_dups.drop(invalid_cancel_tweets.index)

cancel_tweets_clean.to_csv('cancel_tweets_clean.csv')

Below, is VADER sentiment analysis of the cancel culture tweets. We want to see what the postive, negative, and neutral scores are for the cancel tweets. Since a tweet can contain multiple sentences, we break up the tweets into sentences using tokenize.sent_tokenize(tweet.post_text) and store a tuple of the sentences and the post that they come from in different lists depending on which celebrity the cancel tweet is about. After storing the sentiment analysis scores in a dataframe for each celebrity, we average the sentiment analysis scores by post.

In [161]:
# lists to hold sentences of tweets about the three celebrities
james_sentences = []
cardi_sentences = []

for i in range(len(cancel_tweets_clean)):
    
    # store sentences from tweet in sentences
    sentences = tokenize.sent_tokenize(str(cancel_tweets_clean.iloc[i,:].post_text))
    
    # put (sentences, tweet.post_text) in correct lists
    if (cancel_tweets_clean.iloc[i,:].canceled_celeb=='James Charles'):
        james_sentences.append((sentences, cancel_tweets_clean.iloc[i,:].post_text))
    if (cancel_tweets_clean.iloc[i,:].canceled_celeb=='Cardi B'):
        cardi_sentences.append((sentences, cancel_tweets_clean.iloc[i,:].post_text))

paragraphSentiments = 0.0
analyzer = SentimentIntensityAnalyzer()

scores_james = []
posts_james = []

scores_cardi = []
posts_cardi = []

# sentiment analysis for each celebrity
for post in james_sentences:
    for sentence in post[0]:
        vs = analyzer.polarity_scores(sentence)
        scores_james.append(vs)      
        posts_james.append(post[1])

for post in cardi_sentences:
    for sentence in post[0]:
        vs = analyzer.polarity_scores(sentence)
        scores_cardi.append(vs)      
        posts_cardi.append(post[1])
        
# store sentiment analysis score data in dataframes
sent_james = pd.DataFrame(data=scores_james)
sent_james['post_text'] = pd.Series(data=posts_james)

# average sentiment analysis scores by post
james_by_post = sent_james.groupby(['post_text'], as_index=False).mean()

sent_cardi = pd.DataFrame(data=scores_cardi)
sent_cardi['post_text'] = pd.Series(data=posts_cardi)
cardi_by_post = sent_cardi.groupby(['post_text'], as_index=False).mean()

# function to get tweets from the canceled celeb
def get_celeb_tweets(usernames, count, time):
    post_id = []
    post_text = []
    author = []
    date = []
    retweet = []
    favorites = []
    
    for t in time: 
        for username in usernames:
        
            tweetCriteria = got.manager.TweetCriteria().setUsername(username). \
            setSince(t[0]).setUntil(t[1]).setMaxTweets(count)
            tweets = got.manager.TweetManager.getTweets(tweetCriteria)

            for tweet in tweets: 
                post_id.append(tweet.id)
                post_text.append(tweet.text)
                author.append(tweet.username)
                date.append(tweet.date)
                retweet.append(tweet.retweets)
                favorites.append(tweet.favorites)

    data = {'post_id': post_id, 'post_text': post_text, 'author': author, 
            'date': date, 'retweets':retweet, 'favorites': favorites}
    
    celeb_tweets = pd.DataFrame(data=data) 
        
    return celeb_tweets

Our first research question was, is cancel culture a negative phenomenon? After analyzing the sentiment of cancel culture tweets about James Charles and Cardi B as well as tweets from James Charles and Cardi B, we cannot conclude that cancel culture is a negative phenomenon. The highest sentiment category score was neutral when the sentiment scores by post for cancel culture tweets and celebrity tweets were averaged. There is not enough evidence to suggest that cancel culture negatively influences the climate on Twitter. We looked at the cancel culture tweets and celebrity tweets over time from 1/1/2019 to 4/27/2020 and did not see a major change in the negative sentiment score over time. The next step would be to find the anger and negative emotion words in cancel culture tweets using LIWC to better analyze the negativity of these tweets. As we saw in the boxplots of negative sentiment score by post, there were a lot of outliers with high negative sentiment scores. Analyzing these posts with high negative sentiment scores by finding the anger and negative-emotion words in the posts would be beneficial to our analysis. Our follow-up question was, are there any positive aspects to cancel culture? Again, given the average high neutrality score of the cancel-culture and celebrity tweets, we cannot conclude that there are any positive aspects to cancel culture. To analyze the positivity of cancel culture tweets further, we would analyze posts containing words in the positive emotion category using LIWC.

Our next research question is: does being canceled significantly hurt a celebrity's following and status? We plan to analyze this is through likes and comments on the celebrities' YouTube videos, and comments on the celebrities' Instagram posts.¶

# scraping title from youtube video
def get_video_title(soup):
    title = soup.find("h1",{'class':'title style-scope ytd-video-primary-info-renderer'})
    title = title.find("yt-formatted-string",{'class':'style-scope ytd-video-primary-info-renderer'}).get_text()
    return title

# scrapes description from youtube video
def get_description(soup):
    description = soup.find("div",{'id':'description','class':'style-scope ytd-video-secondary-info-renderer'})
    description = description.find("yt-formatted-string",{'class':'style-scope yt-formatted-string'})
    if (description is None):
        description = "NA"
    else:
        description = description.get_text()
    return description

# scrapes username from youtube video
def get_uploader_name(soup):
    name_uploader = soup.find("div",{'id':'upload-info','class':"style-scope ytd-video-owner-renderer"})
    name_uploader = name_uploader.find("a",{'class':'yt-simple-endpoint style-scope yt-formatted-string'}).get_text()
    return name_uploader

# scrapes current views from video
def get_views(soup):
    view = soup.find("span",{'class':'view-count style-scope yt-view-count-renderer'})
    if (view is None):
        view = 0
    else:
        view = view.get_text().split()[0]
    return view

# scrapes date from video
def get_date(soup):
    date = soup.find("div",{'id':'date','class':'style-scope ytd-video-primary-info-renderer'})
    date = date.find("yt-formatted-string",{'class':'style-scope ytd-video-primary-info-renderer'}).get_text()
    return date

# scrapes likes from video
def get_likes(soup):
    likes = soup.find("ytd-sentiment-bar-renderer",{'id':'sentiment','class':"style-scope ytd-video-primary-info-renderer"})
    likes = likes.find("paper-tooltip")
    likes = likes.find('div', {'id': "tooltip"}).get_text()
    likes = likes.rstrip("\n")
    likes = likes.lstrip("\n")
    return likes

#scrapes recommended videos from current video
def get_video_recommendations(soup):
    up_next = {}
    video_recommendations = {}
    block = soup.find_all("a",{'class':'yt-simple-endpoint style-scope ytd-compact-video-renderer'})
    up_next['title'] = block[0].find("span",{'class':'style-scope ytd-compact-video-renderer'}).get('title')
    up_next['url'] = block[0].get('href')
    for i in range(1, len(block)):
        recommendation = {}
        recommendation['title'] = block[i].find("span",{'class':'style-scope ytd-compact-video-renderer'}).get('title')
        recommendation['url'] = block[i].get('href')
        video_recommendations[str(i)] = recommendation
    return up_next,video_recommendations

def get_video_metadata(url):
    browser = create_driver()
    browser.get(url)
    time.sleep(5)
    browser.refresh()
    time.sleep(5)
    #toggle autoplay button is its pressed
    auto_play_button = browser.find_element_by_xpath("//*[@id='toggle']").get_attribute("aria-pressed")
    if auto_play_button == 'true':
        WebDriverWait(browser, 20).until(EC.element_to_be_clickable((By.XPATH, '//*[@id="toggle"]/div[1]'))).click()
    
    # scroll down to end of page to get more results
    html_body = browser.find_element_by_tag_name('html')
    # allows comments to load  
    
    for i in range(0,4):
        for i in range(5):
            html_body.send_keys(Keys.ARROW_DOWN)
        time.sleep(2)
        html_body.send_keys(Keys.END)
        time.sleep(4)
          
    html = browser.page_source
    soup = BeautifulSoup(html, "lxml")
    
    # organizes data into data frame with each comment
    df = pd.DataFrame(columns=["Uploader","Title", "Date", "Views", "Likes/Dislikes","Comments"])
    
    i=0
    for item in browser.find_elements_by_class_name("ytd-comment-thread-renderer"):
        df.loc[i] = [get_uploader_name(soup), get_video_title(soup), get_date(soup), get_views(soup), get_likes(soup), item.text]
        i = i+1
    
    #close driver
    teardown_driver(browser)
    return df;

def splitMultiple(mickle):
    data = mickle.split('\n')
    info = []
    info.append(data[0])
    info.append(data [1])
    comment = ""
    for line in data[2:-2]:
        comment+=line+'\n'
    info.append(comment)
    info.append(data[-2])
    if info[2] == "":
        info[2]=info[3]
        info[3] =0
    return info

import datetime
from dateutil.relativedelta import relativedelta

def get_past_date(str_days_ago):
    TODAY = datetime.date.today()
    splitted = str_days_ago.split()
    if len(splitted) == 1 and splitted[0].lower() == 'today':
        return str(TODAY.isoformat())
    elif len(splitted) == 1 and splitted[0].lower() == 'yesterday':
        date = TODAY - relativedelta(days=1)
        return str(date.isoformat())
    elif splitted[1].lower() in ['hour', 'hours', 'hr', 'hrs', 'h']:
        date = datetime.datetime.now() - relativedelta(hours=int(splitted[0]))
        return str(date.date().isoformat())
    elif splitted[1].lower() in ['day', 'days', 'd']:
        date = TODAY - relativedelta(days=int(splitted[0]))
        return str(date.isoformat())
    elif splitted[1].lower() in ['wk', 'wks', 'week', 'weeks', 'w']:
        date = TODAY - relativedelta(weeks=int(splitted[0]))
        return str(date.isoformat())
    elif splitted[1].lower() in ['mon', 'mons', 'month', 'months', 'm']:
        date = TODAY - relativedelta(months=int(splitted[0]))
        return str(date.isoformat())
    elif splitted[1].lower() in ['yrs', 'yr', 'years', 'year', 'y']:
        date = TODAY - relativedelta(years=int(splitted[0]))
        return str(date.isoformat())
    else:
        return str(TODAY.isoformat())

def to_thousands(likes):   
    if type(likes) is str:        
        if "www.youtube.com" in likes:           
            return 0       
        if "K" in likes:           
            a = likes.replace("K","")           
            temp = 1000*float(a)            
            return int(temp)    
        return likes

# Geting comments and likes from a post of celebrity
def getCommentsAndLikes(name, postNumber, comments):
    
    # Getting profile name
    commentCount = comments
    # Name of profile
    pro = name
    
    # Loading profile name and their page
    profile = instaloader.Profile.from_username(L.context, pro)
    
    # Creating List to track comments and the likes of those comments
    likes = []
    comments = []
    dates = []
    print("Collecting {} comments and likes\n\n".format(pro))
    
    # Iterating over each post of the profile
    for post in itertools.islice(profile.get_posts(), postNumber, postNumber + 1): 
        # Iterating over each comment
        for comment in itertools.islice(post.get_comments(), 250, 250 + commentCount):
            
            # Getting a comment and corresponding likes from different posts  
            likes.append(comment.likes_count)
            comments.append(comment.text)
            dates.append(comment.created_at_utc)  
    return dates, comments, likes

# Creating a table of canceled people 
def createTable(canceled, posts, totalComments):
    df = pd.DataFrame()
    for post in posts:
        df["Post " + str(post) + ": "+ canceled + " Date"], \
            df["Post " + str(post) + ": "+ canceled + " Comments"], \
            df["Post " + str(post) + ": " + canceled + " Likes"] = \
        getCommentsAndLikes(canceled, post, totalComments)

    # Making CSV file
    df.to_csv(canceled + "Canceled.csv")
    # Returning dataframe
    return df

Is cancel culture a negative phenomenon? Are there any positive aspects?¶

From our visualiztions we can see that at least on Instagram, cancel culture results in the celebrity gaining more positive comments after being canceled for both Cardi B and James Charles. This may be because although they may be receiving hate from others, they can also be receiving more positive from fans that are trying to boost the celebrity in forms of positive comments.

Does being “canceled” on social media significantly hurt a celebrity or public figure’s following or status?¶

Along with gaining more positive support in terms of comments from fan we can also see from the scatter plots that overall negative comments seem to be less frequent than positive comments after a celebrity is cancelled. So in regards with the celebrities' statuses, they seems to be viewed more in a positive light after being cancelled.

Conclusion¶

There is not enough data to conclude cancel culture is a negative phenomenon. On Twitter, the sentiment of the cancel culture tweets remained neutral, while on YouTube, the sentiment did become more negative over time. On Instagram, the sentiment increased in positivity over time. We cannot conclude that being canceled permanently damages a celebrity's reputation. To improve our analysis, we should take into account how types of engagement varies on Twitter, YouTube, and Instagram. For example, users might be more likely to post positive comments on Instagram than they are on Twitter which may have been why the sentiment of the Instagram data increased over time despite the celebrities being canceled. We should also take into account how cancel culture is different for social media influencers like James Charles than it is for artists like Cardi B. YouTube is James Charles' main platform, so it is not surprising that his sentiment decreased on YouTube when he was canceled. We should also use LIWC dictionary to find specific words that appear in our data.
